"smart_sources:000 Zettelkasten/PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression..md": {"path":"000 Zettelkasten/PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression..md","class_name":"SmartSource","history":[{"blocks":{"000 Zettelkasten/PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression..md#":true,"000 Zettelkasten/PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression..md#PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression. Applying immune checkpoint inhibitors causes a tumour-suppressive cascade that involves the Ras/Mek/ERK Pathway, PI3K/Akt signalling, as well as downregulation of TCR and CD28 costimulation. However, [[Approximately 30-60% of patients have a resistance to immune checkpoint blockade therapies.]] One method to overcome PD-1 inhibitor resistance is to alter the TME. [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]{1}":true,"000 Zettelkasten/PD-1 inactivation on tumour cells helps promote T-cell function and apoptosis as activation of the PD-1 pathway promotes cancer development and progression..md#References":true},"mtime":1709479565954,"size":955,"hash":"9444f5ed701f9966b92db9e1eb22ab466e4652dfc668265fbb12e97575a9410d"}],"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[-0.00346074,0.00677936,-0.01895111,0.039115,0.03546789,-0.00008225,0.0020479,-0.02511149,-0.00646829,0.00014673,-0